---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from 'astrowind:config';

const crumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { name: 'R&D Center', href: '/randdcenter' },
  { name: 'Textile Performance Testing Lab' },
];

const metadata = {
  title: `Textile Performance Testing Lab — UPF, Waterproof, Breathability & Abrasion Testing | ${SITE.name}`,
  description: `Validate your fabric performance with our textile testing lab. UPF rating, waterproofness, breathability, tensile strength, and abrasion testing. Book a testing session today.`,
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata} breadcrumbs={crumbs}>
  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 py-16 sm:py-20 mx-auto max-w-5xl">
    <a href="/randdcenter" class="text-sm text-gray-500 hover:underline">&larr; Back to R&D Center</a>
    <div class="mt-4 grid md:grid-cols-5 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-3">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary uppercase tracking-wider">Lab 04</p>
        <h1 class="mt-2 text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold">Textile Performance Testing Lab</h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-muted">Validating performance before full-scale production</p>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-2">
        <img
          src="/images/seekingtex/factory/fabric-performance-testing.webp"
          alt="Seekingtex textile performance testing laboratory"
          class="w-full h-48 object-cover rounded-xl"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-12 mx-auto max-w-4xl prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert">
    <h2>Why test fabric performance?</h2>
    <p>
      It is a common misconception that fabric testing is only necessary for high-end technical textiles. In reality, the
      performance of any functional fabric — from outdoor apparel to upholstery to medical textiles — is just as dependent on its
      construction, finish, and coating as any engineered material. UPF rating, waterproofness, breathability, tensile strength, and abrasion resistance all have a
      dramatic effect on the fabric's fit-for-purpose performance and longevity. At {SITE.name}, we operate a dedicated textile
      performance testing lab that allows us to quantify these properties — before committing resources to
      full-scale production.
    </p>
    <p>
      Testing at our facility gives us the ability to iterate fabric constructions and finishes rapidly and
      cost-effectively. A week in the lab can generate the same performance data that would require months of
      production trial-and-error — and at a fraction of the cost.
    </p>

    <h2>Facility specifications</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Specification</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Lab area</td><td>200 m&sup2; climate-controlled (21 &plusmn; 1 &deg;C, 65 &plusmn; 2 % RH)</td></tr>
        <tr
          ><td>UPF testing</td><td
            >UV transmittance analyzer, ASTM D6544 / AATCC 183, UPF 15-50+ rating</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Waterproofness</td><td
            >Hydrostatic head tester, ISO 811, range 0-5000 mbar</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Breathability (MVTR)</td><td
            >Permeability cup system, ASTM E96 (desiccant & water methods), range 500-20000 g/m&sup2;/24h</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Tensile & tear testing</td><td>Universal tester (50 kN), ASTM D5034 (grab test), ASTM D2261 (tongue tear), ASTM D3786 (burst)</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr><td>Abrasion testing</td><td>Martindale abrasion tester, ASTM D4966 / ISO 12947, up to 100 000 cycles</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Our test programme</h2>
    <p>A standard fabric development programme in our lab follows this sequence:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Sample conditioning</strong> — Fabric samples are conditioned in the climate-controlled lab for 24 h at
        standard atmospheric conditions before any test begins.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>UPF rating</strong> — Fabric is measured for UV transmittance across the 290-400 nm spectrum. UPF rating is
        calculated per AATCC 183, with UPF 50+ as the target for sun-protection fabrics.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Waterproofness & breathability</strong> — Hydrostatic head testing measures water penetration resistance. MVTR
        testing measures moisture vapor transmission. The balance between waterproofness and breathability is optimized for each application.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tensile & tear strength</strong> — Grab tensile testing in warp and weft directions. Trapezoid tear testing
        to evaluate tear propagation resistance. Burst strength for knit and non-woven fabrics.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Abrasion resistance (optional)</strong> — Martindale abrasion testing to simulate long-term wear. Samples are
        inspected at regular intervals for surface change, pilling, and breakthrough.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Data analysis & recommendations</strong> — A full report is delivered with comparative charts, performance
        curves, and specific recommendations for the fabric construction or finish.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="not-prose my-10 p-6 rounded-xl bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 mb-3 uppercase tracking-wider">
        Typical Test Results — UPF Rating vs Fabric Construction
      </p>
      <div class="space-y-2">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <span class="w-32">Polyester 150D plain weave</span><div class="flex-1 bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 h-5 rounded">
            <div class="h-full bg-blue-600 rounded" style="width:30%"></div>
          </div><span class="w-16 text-right">UPF 15</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <span class="w-32">Polyester 150D + UV absorber</span><div class="flex-1 bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 h-5 rounded">
            <div class="h-full bg-blue-600 rounded" style="width:60%"></div>
          </div><span class="w-16 text-right">UPF 40</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <span class="w-32">Polyester tight weave + TiO2</span><div class="flex-1 bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 h-5 rounded">
            <div class="h-full bg-blue-600 rounded" style="width:80%"></div>
          </div><span class="w-16 text-right">UPF 50</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <span class="w-32">Nylon ripstop + PU coating</span><div class="flex-1 bg-gray-200 dark:bg-gray-700 h-5 rounded">
            <div class="h-full bg-blue-600 rounded" style="width:100%"></div>
          </div><span class="w-16 text-right">UPF 50+</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-2">
        Fabric construction, fiber type, and UV-blocking additives all contribute to the final UPF rating.
        Our lab optimizes the combination for each application.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Expert team</h2>
    <p>
      Our lab is operated by a textile technologist with a degree in textile engineering and 8 years of performance-testing experience
      at a major international textile testing institute. She is supported by two technicians who prepare all
      samples and instrumentation. The team follows AATCC and ASTM standard procedures to ensure
      that every test is repeatable, traceable, and internationally defensible.
    </p>

    <h2>Testing for custom fabric development</h2>
    <p>
      Our lab is not only used for house-designed fabrics — we regularly run test programmes for clients who want to
      validate a custom fabric construction or investigate a performance issue:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Fabric comparison</strong> — Two or more candidate fabric constructions tested under identical conditions, providing
        an objective performance comparison to inform your selection.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Finish optimization</strong> — Different coating weights, application methods, or curing conditions can be tested to
        quantify their individual contribution to performance.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>End-use suitability study</strong> — Performance data is analyzed against end-use requirements, allowing you to
        select the optimum fabric construction for your target application.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why test with us?</h2>
    <p>
      We do not just give you a set of raw numbers. Our reports translate test data into actionable engineering
      recommendations: "Increase the weave density by 15 % to achieve UPF 50+", "Apply an additional 5 g/m&sup2; of PU coating
      to meet the 1000 mbar waterproofness target", or "Switch to a textured yarn for improved moisture vapor transmission." You leave with a clear understanding of what to change and why.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our lab is also available for independent third-party testing on a fee-for-service basis. If you are developing a
      fabric and want an unbiased, professionally executed performance assessment, we welcome your enquiry.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="px-6 sm:px-6 pb-20 mx-auto max-w-4xl text-center">
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 p-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Book a fabric testing session</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">
        Whether you need a full development programme or a single comparative test, we can accommodate your schedule.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/contact"
        class="mt-4 inline-block px-6 py-3 bg-primary text-white font-semibold rounded-md hover:bg-primary/90"
        >Contact our testing team</a
      >
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
